Islam provides an ethical framework grounded in objective metaphysical necessity. The cosmological argument establishes a single, absolutely simple, transcendent Creator as the logically necessary First Cause. In this framework, moral obligations derive directly from this foundation: they are objective truths discovered through reason and confirmed by revelation, not arbitrary commands or human inventions. Unlike other religions, Islam preserves rigorous divine transcendence while providing a complete, universal ethical system claimed to originate from the very Being whose existence reason necessitates.
In this essay, this framework is operationalized for machine learning. We are using these objective ethical principles to train LLM-based agents in simulated environments (virtual worlds in which agents interact, face moral choices, and learn their consequences). The simulation provides empirical feedback for reinforcement learning while the Islamic ethical structure supplies the ground truth: a fixed, non-arbitrary value function derived from divine legislation rather than human preference or utilitarian calculus. Agents trained in this environment internalize objective morality through experiential learning, aligning their behavior with rationally necessitated ethical constraints.
